259","1366":"1366","1255":"1255","1299":"1299","1288":"1288","1277":"1277","1276":"1276","1287":"1287","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Nantwich, Cheshire, England":"Nantwich, Cheshire, England","Egerton, Cheshire, England":"Egerton, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1285–":"1285–Deceased","1277–1362":"1277–1362","1281–Male":"1281–Deceased","1284–1326":"1284–1326","1285–Female":"1285–Deceased","1285–Male":"1285–Deceased","1287–Male":"1287–Deceased","1288–Female":"1288–Deceased","1288–Male":"1288–Deceased","1292–1366":"1292–1366","1299–1362":"1299–1362","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1255–1315":"1255–1315","1259–1318":"1259–1318","1285":"1285","1362":"1362","1284":"1284","1292":"1292","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","1259":"1259","1366":"1366","1255":"1255","1299":"1299","1288":"1288","1277":"1277","1276":"1276","1287":"1287","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","England":"England, United Kingdom","Nantwich, Cheshire, England":"Nantwich, Cheshire, England","Egerton, Cheshire, England":"Egerton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Egerton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Cheshire and Lancashire): variant of   Edgerton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edgerton","meanings":["English (West Midlands): habitational name from any of various places called Egerton in Cheshire and Kent, Egerton in Wheathill (Shropshire), Egerton in Bolton le Moors (Lancashire), Egerton in Scammonden (Yorkshire), or Edgerton in Huddersfield (Yorkshire). Egerton in Kent is from the Old English personal name <i>Ecgheard</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘estate, farmstead’ (see   Eckert  ), but Egerton in Chesire is more likely to derive from the Old English personal name <i>Ecghere</i> (in which the second element is Old English <i>here</i> ‘army’) + Old English <i>tūn</i>."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":5,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":30,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":43,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan de Egerton was born in 1285, in Nantwich, Cheshire, England, her father, Phillip de Egerton, was 31 and her mother, Lady Margaret De Wrenbury x, was 26. She had at least 1 daughter with Mr Payne. She died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1285–":"1285–Surnud","1277–1362":"1277–1362","1281–Male":"1281–Surnud","1284–1326":"1284–1326","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1288–Female":"1288–Surnud","1288–Male":"1288–Surnud","1292–1366":"1292–1366","1299–1362":"1299–1362","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1255–1315":"1255–1315","1259–1318":"1259–1318","1285":"1285","1362":"1362","1284":"1284","1292":"1292","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1326":"13